    "body": "Some thoughts after reading this in detail\r\n- when status gets a EIP681 link, this link does not have information about which account to use (and it makes sense!) it's up to status UI to allow the user to chose from which account this will be paid\r\n- The account could thus be any of the accounts from the user excepting read-only accounts \r\n- regarding the ability to open status from a link on the keycard request screen I see different options \r\ni. we use a eip681 link to specify the amount and asset to transfer, and we either specify with an extra parameter (we're thus extending eip681 in the link) that any keycard should be able to sign this, or let the user chose which account to use to sign in the status UI (makes sense anyway since we are now multiaccount)\r\nii. we don't use eip681 links for this but rather a link to a dApp, this dApp being super simple and a call to web3.signtypedData(details of the transaction to sign) which pops up the request screen. The dApp is then the one to decide what to do with the meta-tx (send it with gas abstraction to a user wallet etc.)\r\n\r\nI actually think that only option ii. makes sense because \r\n- in i. until we have defined a payment network to be used within status, we don't know what to do with the information provided to status (we have the amount to transfer, and a keycard EOA to sign a meta tx BUT no user wallet to use)\r\n- ii. doesn't need any extra development and is quite generic wrgds to which payment network is used. \r\n\r\ncc @bitgamma cc @gravityblast @hesterbruikman ",
