    "body": "ðŸ‘† Exactly, a dedicated payment app (other than the Status merchant dapp) uses a link to create a payment request that the buyer then signs on their own device. Considering the numerous merchant apps already out there, integrating with inventory, accounting, etc.. From a merchant's perspective it would be way more convenient to send a payment request from their existing UI than to have to 'get into web3'.\r\n\r\n- Buyer provides digital or physical shopping card\r\n- Merchant app generates payment url (+QR code)\r\n- Merchant sends url or shows QR code\r\n- Buyer taps on url or scans code\r\n- Client shows Keycard sign request screen\r\n- Buyer signs and shares confirmation\r\n\r\nFor reference, this is the standard in The Netherlands for creating interbank payment requests: https://www.ideal.nl/en/consumers/ideal-payment-request/. It's more or less the flow I have in mind\r\n\r\nTangential, another scenario would be more relevant when the user can merge Keycard MA and regular MA (#10128)\r\n- User A sends request\r\n- User B selects Keycard account (in case of multiple accounts)\r\n- Client prompts Keycard signing",
